      <span aria-current="page">Sargon vs Lugalzagesi</span>
    </nav>

    <section>
      <p>
        Around 2334 BCE, Sargon of Akkad marched south to confront Lugalzagesi, the last king who had unified Sumer 
        under his rule. Sargonâ€™s victory ended Lugalzagesiâ€™s Sumerian state, initiating the Akkadian Empire and reshaping 
        Mesopotamian politics for the next two centuries.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Historical context</h2>
      <p>
        Lugalzagesi had temporarily united Sumerian city-states, but Akkad to the north was rising in power under Sargon. 
        The campaign represents the first recorded conquest of a Sumerian king by an Akkadian ruler, establishing the precedent 
        for imperial expansion.
      </p>
      <h3>Principal actors</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sargon of Akkad:</strong> ambitious ruler and military strategist, founder of the Akkadian Empire.</li>
        <li><strong>Lugalzagesi:</strong> King of Umma, formerly unifier of Sumer, defeated in the decisive battle.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Sources & evidence</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Sumerian King List recording the end of Lugalzagesiâ€™s reign and the rise of Sargon.</li>
        <li>Royal inscriptions of Sargon celebrating the conquest of Sumerian cities.</li>
        <li>Archaeological evidence of destruction layers in Uruk, Ur, and other key Sumerian sites.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Campaign narrative (reconstructed)</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Advance:</strong> Sargon marches from Akkad with a well-organized army north to south, targeting Sumerian cities.</li>
        <li><strong>Engagement:</strong> Lugalzagesi attempts to defend his territories; key battles occur at Uruk and Umma.</li>
        <li><strong>Victory:</strong> Sargon defeats Lugalzagesi, captures him, and proclaims Akkadian authority over Sumer.</li>
        <li><strong>Aftermath:</strong> Akkadian rule replaces Sumerian city-state autonomy; the city-states retain local administrators but acknowledge Sargonâ€™s empire.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Military organization</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Sargonâ€™s forces utilize infantry, war wagons, and coordination across multiple city-states.</li>
        <li>Elite Akkadian troops secure key strategic points and suppress resistance.</li>
        <li>Use of propaganda, including inscriptions and public executions, to consolidate control.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Political and ideological significance</h2>
      <p>
        The fall of Lugalzagesi demonstrates the fragility of city-state unification and the effectiveness of centralized imperial power. 
        Sargonâ€™s victory sets the stage for the Akkadian Empire, linking military success with divine sanction and political legitimacy.
      </p>
    </section>

